SIMPLE: orthography
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Orthography
<hw>Or*thog"ra*phy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>ortographie</ets>, OF. <ets>orthographie</ets>, L.
<ets>orthographia</ets>, Gr. <?/, fr. <?/ writing correctly;
<grk>'orqo`s</grk> right + <grk>gra`fein</grk> to write. See
<er>Ortho-</er>, and <er>Graphic</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The art or practice of writing words with the proper
letters, according to standard usage; conventionally correct spelling;
also, mode of spelling; <as>as, his <ex>orthography</ex> is
vicious</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When spelling no longer follows the pronunciation, but is hardened
into <qex>orthography</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Earle.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The part of grammar which treats of the letters, and
of the art of spelling words correctly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A drawing in correct projection, especially an
elevation or a vertical section.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The method of spelling the words of a particular
language; the system of symbols used for writing a language.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The branch of linguistics concerned with how
languages are written.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Orthology</ent>⟦br⟧
